ps every URL to its rejection reason"},"1076":{"id":"sdk-133","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#typed-errors","content":"`IndexerHttpError`"},"1077":{"id":"sdk-134","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#typed-errors","content":"An indexer endpoint responded non-2xx; carries `.status` and the indexer's own `.indexerCode`. The scan treats it as \"fall back to the Horizon walk\""},"1078":{"id":"sdk-135","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#typed-errors","content":"`IndexerNetworkError`"},"1079":{"id":"sdk-136","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#typed-errors","content":"An indexer was unreachable at the transport level (DNS/refused/timeout/invalid body); same Horizon fallback"},"1080":{"id":"sdk-137","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#helpers","content":"Helper"},"1081":{"id":"sdk-138","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#helpers","content":"Purpose"},"1082":{"id":"sdk-139","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#helpers","content":"`parseStroops(s)` / `numberToStroops(n)` / `formatStroops(b)`"},"1083":{"id":"sdk-140","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#helpers","content":"Exact stroop conversion (no float drift)"},"1084":{"id":"sdk-141","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#helpers","content":"`resolveTokenAddress(asset, passphrase)`"},"1085":{"id":"sdk-142","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#helpers","content":"`'native'` / `'CODE:ISSUER'` → SAC contract address"},"1086":{"id":"sdk-143","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#helpers","content":"`labelForToken(address, passphrase)`"},"1087":{"id":"sdk-144","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#helpers","content":"Native SAC address → `'XLM'`; otherwise unchanged"},"1088":{"id":"sdk-145","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#helpers","content":"`prepareWithRestore(...)`"},"1089":{"id":"sdk-146","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#helpers","content":"Restore-aware Soroban prepare (see Architecture)"},"1090":{"id":"sdk-147","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#helpers","content":"`HorizonClient`"},"1091":{"id":"sdk-148","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#helpers","content":"Injectable-fetch Horizon wrapper (testable offline)"},"1092":{"id":"sdk-149","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#helpers","content":"`PoolAdapter` / `AccountAdapter`"},"1093":{"id":"sdk-150","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#helpers","content":"The delivery adapters, if you need them directly"},"1094":{"id":"sdk-151","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#shadecrypto","content":"The primitives live in `@shade/crypto`. That package is **not published to\nnpm**: it is bundled into `stellar-shade` at build time, and the SDK re-exports\nonly a small part of its surface. The import below therefore works **inside this\nmonorepo**, where workspaces resolve the name; it is not something an outside\nconsumer can install:"},"1095":{"id":"sdk-152","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#types","content":"All six exported types work in **raw bytes** (`Uint8Array`), not hex strings:"},"1096":{"id":"sdk-153","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#types","content":"`@shade/crypto`"},"1097":{"id":"sdk-154","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#types","content":"`stellar-shade`"},"1098":{"id":"sdk-155","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#types","content":"Encoding"},"1099":{"id":"sdk-156","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#types","content":"`Uint8Array` (raw bytes)"},"1100":{"id":"sdk-157","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#types","content":"`string` (hex)"},"1101":{"id":"sdk-158","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#types","content":"Fields"},"1102":{"id":"sdk-159","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#types","content":"`spendPrivKey`, `viewPrivKey`, `metaAddress` (an object)"},"1103":{"id":"sdk-160","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#types","content":"`metaAddress` (a `shade:stellar:` string), `spendPubKey`, `spendPrivKey`, `viewPubKey`, `viewPrivKey`"},"1104":{"id":"sdk-161","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#types","content":"`StealthClient.keygen()` returns the **SDK** shape; `generateMetaAddress()` returns the **crypto*&#x2A; shape. Passing one where the other is expected will not type-check. Convert the crypto shape with the exported &#x2A;*`stealthKeysFromRaw(raw)`*&#x2A; helper, and import the crypto type under a distinct name via the re-export &#x2A;*`RawStealthKeys`**, so mixed-use code has one unambiguous import site. Both are re-exported from `stellar-shade`. </Callout>"},"1105":{"id":"sdk-162","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#types","content":"Errors: `InvalidPublicKey`, `InvalidScalar`, `InvalidMetaAddress`, `PointAtInfinity`."},"1106":{"id":"sdk-163","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#next-steps","content":"Core Concepts: the math behind these functions"},"1107":{"id":"sdk-164","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#next-steps","content":"Delivery Methods: what `method` changes"},"1108":{"id":"sdk-165","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#next-steps","content":"Relayer: the service `RelayerClient` talks to"},"1109":{"id":"sdk-166","page_id":"sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk#next-steps","content":"FAQ & Troubleshooting: error-by-error fixes"},"1110":{"id":"security","page_id":"security","type":"page","content":"Security","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","Trust"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/security"},"1111":{"id":"security-0","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security","content":"Shade's threat model: what stealth addresses protect, what they explicitly do not hide, key-management assumptions, audit status and known limitations."},"1112":{"id":"security-1","page_id":"security","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/security#status-pre-audit-not-for-mainnet","content":"Status: pre-audit, not for mainnet"},"1113":{"id":"security-2","page_id":"security","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/security#threat-model","content":"Threat model"},"1114":{"id":"security-3","page_id":"security","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"What Shade protects"},"1115":{"id":"security-4","page_id":"security","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/security#what-shade-does-not-protect","content":"What Shade does NOT protect"},"1116":{"id":"security-5","page_id":"security","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/security#key-management-assumptions","content":"Key-management assumptions"},"1117":{"id":"security-6","page_id":"security","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/security#the-raw-scalar-footgun","content":"The raw-scalar footgun"},"1118":{"id":"security-7","page_id":"security","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/security#wallet-derived-keys-an-accepted-trade-off","content":"Wallet-derived keys: an accepted trade-off"},"1119":{"id":"security-8","page_id":"security","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/security#no-view-key-revocation","content":"No view-key revocation"},"1120":{"id":"security-9","page_id":"security","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/security#cryptographic-notes","content":"Cryptographic notes"},"1121":{"id":"security-10","page_id":"security","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/security#known-limitations-and-open-risks","content":"Known limitations and open risks"},"1122":{"id":"security-11","page_id":"security","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/security#protocol--product","content":"Protocol / product"},"1123":{"id":"security-12","page_id":"security","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/security#implementation-gaps-worth-knowing","content":"Implementation gaps worth knowing"},"1124":{"id":"security-13","page_id":"security","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/security#user-responsibility","content":"User responsibility"},"1125":{"id":"security-14","page_id":"security","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/security#reporting","content":"Reporting"},"1126":{"id":"security-15","page_id":"security","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/security#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1127":{"id":"security-16","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security","content":"\\{/\\* adapted from shade\\@36217c4 docs/09-security.md \\*/}"},"1128":{"id":"security-17","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security","content":"import \\{ Callout } from 'fumadocs-ui/components/callout';"},"1129":{"id":"security-18","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security","content":"What Shade protects, what it explicitly does not, and what you must not rely on yet. Read this page before putting value at risk."},"1130":{"id":"security-19","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#status-pre-audit-not-for-mainnet","content":"The protocol and this implementation have **not undergone an external cryptographic audit**. An audit is on the roadmap. Treat the library as production-track but pre-audit, and **do not handle mainnet value**."},"1131":{"id":"security-20","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#status-pre-audit-not-for-mainnet","content":"The **pool** method has been exercised end-to-end on Stellar **testnet** with **native XLM**. The pool contract is **asset-agnostic**: it calls the standard SAC token interface (`token::Client`) with the token address as a parameter, so a classic asset such as USDC takes the identical path, differing only in that address. No testnet contract id is pinned (testnet resets quarterly, so deploy your own). The **account** method's cold-scan bottleneck, where its scan (and `balance`) walk the global Horizon transaction feed, is addressed by the announcement indexer; by design every scan ends with a Horizon tail, so an unreachable or degraded indexer falls back to the plain walk. Without an indexer, a cold account scan remains impractical at public-network scale."},"1132":{"id":"security-21","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"Property"},"1133":{"id":"security-22","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"How"},"1134":{"id":"security-23","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"**Recipient identity**"},"1135":{"id":"security-24","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"A stealth address is unlinkable to a meta-address without the view key. An observer sees `sender → contract` (pool) or `sender → one-time account` (account), plus `R` and `stealth_pk`, none of which reveal *you*."},"1136":{"id":"security-25","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"**Unlinkability between payments**"},"1137":{"id":"security-26","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"Each payment uses a fresh random ephemeral `r`, so two stealth addresses for the same recipient look unrelated."},"1138":{"id":"security-27","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"**Your funded accounts**"},"1139":{"id":"security-28","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"A relayer fee-bump means your own wallet never appears on the withdrawal."},"1140":{"id":"security-29","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"**Spend/view separation**"},"1141":{"id":"security-30","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"The view key can find payments but never move them, so it is safe to delegate to a scanner."},"1142":{"id":"security-31","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"**Replay across deployments/networks**"},"1143":{"id":"security-32","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"The withdraw message binds the contract address **and** the network id, so a signature valid on one deployment is rejected on another."},"1144":{"id":"security-33","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"**Replay of the same withdrawal**"},"1145":{"id":"security-34","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"A strictly-increasing per-key nonce in contract storage."},"1146":{"id":"security-35","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"**Reentrancy on withdraw**"},"1147":{"id":"security-36","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"Checks-effects-interactions: nonce and balance are committed before the external SAC `transfer`."},"1148":{"id":"security-37","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"**Small-subgroup attacks**"},"1149":{"id":"security-38","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"`validatePoint` accepts only on-curve, **torsion-free** points, rejecting the identity and small-order points on every path that touches `R`, `K_view`, `K_spend`."},"1150":{"id":"security-39","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"**Announcement spam**"},"1151":{"id":"security-40","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"Deposit and announcement are atomic: no deposit, no announcement."},"1152":{"id":"security-41","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"**Malicious relayer (sponsored claim)**"},"1153":{"id":"security-42","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"The client re-derives the expected operation list from its own trusted inputs and refuses to sign a mismatch (`SponsoredClaimMismatchError`)."},"1154":{"id":"security-43","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"**Malicious indexer (account discovery)**"},"1155":{"id":"security-44","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"An indexer can *hide* payments (an availability failure) but cannot *fabricate* them: the client derives the stealth address from `R` itself and re-verifies on-chain at claim. It serves no address- or R-keyed queries, so the operator cannot link keys to requests; every scan ends with a Horizon tail and falls back to Horizon on any fault."},"1156":{"id":"security-45","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"**Tampered session storage**"},"1157":{"id":"security-46","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-protects","content":"On unlock, public keys are re-derived from the decrypted private scalars and compared (`SessionIntegrityError`)."},"1158":{"id":"security-47","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-does-not-protect","content":"Not protected"},"1159":{"id":"security-48","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-does-not-protect","content":"Why"},"1160":{"id":"security-49","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-does-not-protect","content":"**Amounts**"},"1161":{"id":"security-50","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-does-not-protect","content":"Deposit and withdrawal amounts are public on-chain."},"1162":{"id":"security-51","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-does-not-protect","content":"**The fact a payment occurred**"},"1163":{"id":"security-52","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-does-not-protect","content":"Fully visible."},"1164":{"id":"security-53","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-does-not-protect","content":"**Fund flow**"},"1165":{"id":"security-54","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-does-not-protect","content":"**Shade is not a mixer.** A pool deposit and its withdrawal both name the same `stealth_pk`, so the flow is traceable. Only the link to your identity is hidden."},"1166":{"id":"security-55","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-does-not-protect","content":"**Timing correlation**"},"1167":{"id":"security-56","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-does-not-protect","content":"Withdraw immediately after a deposit and the link is obvious."},"1168":{"id":"security-57","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-does-not-protect","content":"**Amount-pattern correlation**"},"1169":{"id":"security-58","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-does-not-protect","content":"Distinctive amounts correlate deposits and withdrawals."},"1170":{"id":"security-59","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-does-not-protect","content":"**The withdrawal destination**"},"1171":{"id":"security-60","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-does-not-protect","content":"Public, though it can be a fresh address with no history."},"1172":{"id":"security-61","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-does-not-protect","content":"**Your behaviour**"},"1173":{"id":"security-62","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#what-shade-does-not-protect","content":"Address reuse, a linked fee-payer, or a known destination will deanonymize you regardless of the cryptography."},"1174":{"id":"security-63","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#key-management-assumptions","content":"**Spend private keys never leave the client.**"},"1175":{"id":"security-64","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#key-management-assumptions","content":"**View keys enable scan-only access.** Safe to delegate, but see the revocation limit below."},"1176":{"id":"security-65","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#key-management-assumptions","content":"**Stealth private keys exist only in memory** during a claim/withdraw."},"1177":{"id":"security-66","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#key-management-assumptions","content":"**All randomness** comes from the platform CSPRNG (`crypto.getRandomValues()` / `randomBytes`)."},"1178":{"id":"security-67","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#key-management-assumptions","content":"**Keystores are encrypted by default** with AES-256-GCM (scrypt `N=131072, r=8, p=1`, files mode `0600`); `--plaintext` opts out."},"1179":{"id":"security-68","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#key-management-assumptions","content":"**Browser sessions** use PBKDF2-SHA256 (600k) → AES-256-GCM; only public keys are stored in the clear."},"1180":{"id":"security-69","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#wallet-derived-keys-an-accepted-trade-off","content":"With the wallet-signature path, **wallet compromise equals stealth-key compromise**: anyone who can produce the signature can re-derive the keys. That is the accepted deal for keyless recovery."},"1181":{"id":"security-70","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#wallet-derived-keys-an-accepted-trade-off","content":"Two hard rules:"},"1182":{"id":"security-71","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#wallet-derived-keys-an-accepted-trade-off","content":"**Never sign the derivation message anywhere you don't trust.** Signing it hands over the ability to derive (and control) your stealth keys. The message includes an explicit warning line for exactly this reason."},"1183":{"id":"security-72","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#wallet-derived-keys-an-accepted-trade-off","content":"**The signer must be deterministic** (RFC 8032). A randomized signer derives different, unrecoverable keys on every call. The SDK verifies determinism by default (signs twice and compares) rather than letting you find out later."},"1184":{"id":"security-73","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#cryptographic-notes","content":"**Curve:** ed25519, order `L = 2^252 + 27742317777372353535851937790883648493`."},"1185":{"id":"security-74","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#cryptographic-notes","content":"**Primitives:** `@noble/curves` / `@noble/hashes` (the same audited primitives used broadly across the Stellar ecosystem) plus `@scure/bip39`."},"1186":{"id":"security-75","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#cryptographic-notes","content":"**The ECDH runs client-side by necessity.** Soroban's host exposes `ed25519_verify`, `sha256`, `secp256r1_verify`, and curve operations for **BLS12-381** (CAP-0059) and **BN254**, but **no Curve25519 scalar-multiplication host function**. The contract only ever *verifies* an ed25519 signature."},"1187":{"id":"security-76","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#cryptographic-notes","content":"**No BIP-32/44.** HD derivation uses domain-separated SHA-256, not standard BIP-32 paths (those are defined over secp256k1). Recovery works within Shade's own scheme."},"1188":{"id":"security-77","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#cryptographic-notes","content":"**Deterministic signing.** `signWithStealthKey` builds an RFC 8032-style signature directly from the raw scalar, with a deterministic nonce `r = SHA-512(scalar ‖ message) mod L`. Signatures verify with standard `ed25519.verify`."},"1189":{"id":"security-78","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#cryptographic-notes","content":"**Amount encryption** (`encryptAmount` / `decryptAmount`) is encrypt-then-MAC (XOR keystream + HMAC-SHA256) with constant-time tag verification. It is **not used by the pool contract**; it exists for applications built on top."},"1190":{"id":"security-79","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#protocol--product","content":"**Destination account must exist.** A pool withdrawal needs an active Stellar destination (its own \\~1 XLM reserve). Fund it via an exchange withdrawal for best privacy, or use a relayer-sponsored claim."},"1191":{"id":"security-80","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#protocol--product","content":"**No external audit.**"},"1192":{"id":"security-81","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#implementation-gaps-worth-knowing","content":"**Relayer defaults are secure, but explicit overrides can weaken them.** Credit gating is **on by default on every network**; explicitly setting `RELAYER_REQUIRE_CREDIT=0` leaves `/relay` and `/sponsor-claim/submit` unauthenticated. `CORS_ORIGIN` defaults to `*` (a startup warning fires). `RELAYER_SECRET` is **always required**: the relayer fails fast (exit 1) if it is unset, rather than booting an unfunded random keypair. `NETWORK` defaults to `testnet` and rejects unknown values (including the removed `local`). See Relayer."},"1193":{"id":"security-82","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#implementation-gaps-worth-knowing","content":"**Relayer state is durable/shared only when configured.** By default the credit ledger is a JSON file (wiped by an ephemeral-filesystem restart, taking consumed-tx idempotency with it) and challenge nonces + rate-limit buckets are in-memory. Set `DATABASE_URL` (Postgres) to make the ledger durable and multi-instance, and `REDIS_URL` (Redis) to share nonces + rate limits across instances; both fail fast if set-but-unreachable rather than silently forking the ledger. See Durable & multi-instance state."},"1194":{"id":"security-83","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#implementation-gaps-worth-knowing","content":"**State archival.** If a `Balance`/`Nonce` entry archives, a withdraw over the archived footprint fails on-chain while `get_balance` still reports the funds. The SDK restores automatically; if the restore itself fails you get `EntryArchivedRestoringError`. **The funds are safe**, but the withdraw can't proceed until the entry is restored. Read-path TTL extension (`get_balance`/`get_nonce` bump a live entry back to \\~1 year) makes this unlikely for anyone who scans periodically."},"1195":{"id":"security-84","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#user-responsibility","content":"The cryptography gives you the tools; you can still deanonymize yourself:"},"1196":{"id":"security-85","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#user-responsibility","content":"**Vary timing.** Don't withdraw right after a deposit."},"1197":{"id":"security-86","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#user-responsibility","content":"**Vary amounts.** Partial withdrawals reduce correlation with the original deposit."},"1198":{"id":"security-87","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#user-responsibility","content":"**Use fresh destination addresses** with no history."},"1199":{"id":"security-88","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#user-responsibility","content":"**Never pay the fee from an account linked to you.** That's what the relayer is for."},"1200":{"id":"security-89","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#user-responsibility","content":"**Guard your view key.** Sharing it is permanent."},"1201":{"id":"security-90","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#reporting","content":"This project is pre-audit and provided as-is."},"1202":{"id":"security-91","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#next-steps","content":"Core Concepts: the cryptography these guarantees rest on"},"1203":{"id":"security-92","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#next-steps","content":"Architecture: where each control is implemented"},"1204":{"id":"security-93","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#next-steps","content":"Relayer: operational hardening"},"1205":{"id":"security-94","page_id":"security","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/security#next-steps","content":"FAQ & Troubleshooting: what specific errors mean"}},"count":1205},"sorting":{"language":"english","sortableProperties":["content","page_id","type","url"],"sortablePropertiesWithTypes":{"content":"string","page_id":"string","type":"string","url":"string"},"sorts":{"content":{"docs":{"1":550,"2":990,"3":602,"4":1080,"5":898,"6":1024,"7":562,"8":1115,"9":929,"10":1019,"11":631,"12":946,"13":630,"14":1049,"15":1144,"16":596,"17":620,"18":683,"19":605,"20":1181,"21":838,"22":181,"23":762,"24":989,"25":112,"26":869,"27":949,"28":787,"29":246,"30":669,"31":177,"32":457,"33":456,"3